04394nam a22005415i 9780300150513DE-B159720220524034747.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220524t19941994ctu    fo  d z      eng d  a97803001505137 a10.12987/97803001505132doi  a(DE-B1597)486529  a(OCoLC)1024023525  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  actucUS-CT 4aDS135.P62bW33613 1994eb 7aHIS0271002bisacsh04a940.53/43842221 a(Simha Rotem), Kazik, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMemoirs of a Warsaw Ghetto Fighter /cKazik (Simha Rotem); ed. by Barbara Harshav. 1aNew Haven, CT : bYale University Press, c[1994] 4cÂ©1994  a1 online resource (196 p.) :b10 b/w illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  a"In the first three days [of the Warsaw Ghetto uprising], the Germans didn't take a single Jew out of the buildings. After their attempts to penetrate the Ghetto had failed, they decided to spare themselves casualties by destroying it from outside with cannon and aerial bombings. A few days later the Ghetto was totally destroyed. . . . The 'streets' were nothing but rows of smoldering ruins. It was hard to cross them without stepping on charred bodies."-KazikWhen the Nazis decided to liquidate the Warsaw Ghetto in 1943, five hundred young Jewish fighters within the Ghetto rose up to defy them. With no weapons, no influence, and no experience in warfare, they managed to resist the Germans for almost a month. In the end, when the battle was lost, the surviving Jews were led out of the ruins through the sewers by a nineteen-year-old fighter known as Kazik. As head courier of the Jewish Fighting Organization (ZOB), which had planned and executed the uprising, Kazik spent the rest of the war helping to care for the several thousand Jews who still remained in Warsaw. This book-an extraordinary story of courage and perseverance-is Kazik's wartime memoir.In stark, spare detail, Kazik reports on the efforts to prepare for the defense of the Warsaw Ghetto, the calamitous battle with the Germans, and the rescue of the few Jews who were still alive after the Ghetto was destroyed. He describes how he assumed a false Aryan identity in order to pass through the city as he collected money and found hiding places for the survivors. Constantly on guard, fearful of informers, his life always in danger, he nevertheless plotted resourcefully to aid his fellow Jews. He tells how he joined the Poles during their ill-fated uprising against the Nazis in Warsaw in 1944, had further brushes with death assisting the Polish underground, and returned to Warsaw to watch its liberation by the Russian army.Suspenseful, moving, and remarkably heroic, Kazik's memoir is only the second source to be published on the Warsaw Ghetto Uprising. It will help demolish the image of Jews as submissive victims in the Holocaust.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aHolocaust, Jewish (1939-1945)zPolandzWarsawvPersonal narratives. 0aJewsxPersecutionszPolandzWarsaw. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xJewish resistancezPoland. 7aHISTORY / Military / World War II.2bisacsh1 aHarshav, Barbara, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press eBook-Package Archive Pre-2000z978311053801440uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/978030015051340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300150513423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300150513/original  a978-3-11-053801-4  Yale University Press eBook-Package Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles